  "articleSummary": "The article argues that JavaScript promises are not “broken” – the persistent myth stems from outdated misconceptions and poor examples rather than any inherent flaw in the API. It debunks the error‑handling myth by showing how proper use of `return`, real `Error` objects, and `.catch()` restores reliable flow, and it adds style guidance (e.g., preferring named functions) to make promise chains clearer and more testable. The piece is aimed at web developers and JavaScript learners who already know async basics, and it adopts an instructional‑analysis tone, repeatedly framing the discussion as a “myth‑busting” narrative (“Before Times” vs. “Now Times”) while using the metaphor of promises needing something to “hang on to.”",
